## 3. `--dangerously-skip-permissions` and Hooks

### Worker launch commands (from shell/doey-team-mgmt.sh and shell/doey-session.sh):

All Doey roles are launched with `--dangerously-skip-permissions`:

```bash
# Workers (shell/doey-team-mgmt.sh:474)
claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --effort high --model $_bbw_worker_model --name "T${team_window} W${worker_num}"

# Subtaskmaster (shell/doey-team-mgmt.sh:776)
claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --model $mgr_model --name "${_mgr_name}" --agent "$mgr_agent"

# Boss (shell/doey-session.sh:143)
claude --dangerously-skip-permissions --model ${DOEY_BOSS_MODEL:-$DOEY_TASKMASTER_MODEL} --name "Boss" --agent doey-boss

# Taskmaster, Task Reviewer, Deployment — all have --dangerously-skip-permissions
```

### Effect on hooks:
`--dangerously-skip-permissions` **only affects tool permission prompts** (the "Allow Claude to run this command? [y/N]" UI). It does NOT:
- Skip hook execution
- Auto-accept hook blocks (exit 1/2)
- Suppress hook system-reminders

**Hooks always run regardless of permission mode.** This is by design — hooks are project-level safety guardrails that cannot be bypassed.

